1
00:00:07.540 --> 00:00:09.780
I can't emphasize that enough.

2
00:00:09.780 --> 00:00:14.400
You can have all the technical knowledge in the world, but if the user had a poor experience

3
00:00:14.400 --> 00:00:18.240
in the process of getting their issues solved, you failed.

4
00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:22.520
The techniques will discuss in these videos won't only help you with your users, the help

5
00:00:22.520 --> 00:00:28.580
you work better with your peers, your managers, and maybe even your own personal relationships.

6
00:00:28.580 --> 00:00:32.880
Keep in mind, these techniques don't work in all situations.

7
00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:37.960
The reality is that no matter how great you are at customer service, some situations don't

8
00:00:37.960 --> 00:00:39.860
have a good resolution.

9
00:00:39.860 --> 00:00:44.760
Plus, everyone is different, so you'll need to tweak your style when working with users.

10
00:00:44.760 --> 00:00:49.780
But the techniques will cover are intended to make your IT interactions more successful.

11
00:00:49.780 --> 00:00:54.800
In IT support, you work with users to fix technology and improve how people use it.

12
00:00:54.800 --> 00:00:58.560
To accomplish this, you need to develop a trust between you and the user.

13
00:00:58.580 --> 00:01:04.580
Lots of employers believe that good customer service also builds brown loyalty, which is a key to success.

14
00:01:04.580 --> 00:01:11.580
These lessons are meant to give you the foundational skills and techniques of how to deliver great customer service.

15
00:01:11.580 --> 00:01:15.580
Customer service practices can differ from company to company.

16
00:01:15.580 --> 00:01:20.580
So while we'll cover the key concepts of customer service in any IT support role,

17
00:01:20.580 --> 00:01:24.580
it's important to talk with your employer to understand the company's customer service approach.

18
00:01:24.580 --> 00:01:28.560
This will also give you an idea of how much freedom or restrictions you will also give you an idea of how much freedom or restrictions you

19
00:01:28.580 --> 00:01:29.980
you might have in the role.

20
00:01:29.980 --> 00:01:33.120
Spoiler alert, great customer service requires

21
00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:36.500
exhibiting empathy, being conscious of your tone,

22
00:01:36.500 --> 00:01:38.600
acknowledging the person you're talking to,

23
00:01:38.600 --> 00:01:40.780
and developing trust with the user.

24
00:01:40.780 --> 00:01:43.480
If you remember nothing else from this lesson,

25
00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:45.620
remember those four things.

26
00:01:45.620 --> 00:01:48.080
The most important of all of these is empathy.

27
00:01:48.080 --> 00:01:50.920
What's the difference between sympathy and empathy?

28
00:01:50.920 --> 00:01:52.540
People will say things like,

29
00:01:52.540 --> 00:01:56.080
sympathy is saying you're sorry, empathy is feeling sorry.

30
00:01:56.080 --> 00:01:57.760
That doesn't really explain it.

31
00:01:57.760 --> 00:02:00.320
So let's use an example to drive this home.

32
00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:04.180
If someone fell into a dark, damp, dirty hole,

33
00:02:04.180 --> 00:02:07.520
and you leaned over with a sad expression and said,

34
00:02:07.520 --> 00:02:10.759
that must be a really tough situation.

35
00:02:10.759 --> 00:02:12.460
Then you're expressing sympathy.

36
00:02:12.460 --> 00:02:13.840
You're sharing their feelings,

37
00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:16.720
but you aren't experiencing those feelings.

38
00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:20.180
If you crawled down into that dark, damp, dirty hole

39
00:02:20.180 --> 00:02:22.800
with the person who fell and said,

40
00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:25.680
this is a really tough situation.

41
00:02:25.680 --> 00:02:27.540
Then you're expressing empathy.

42
00:02:27.540 --> 00:02:31.260
you're able to see something from someone else's perspective

43
00:02:31.260 --> 00:02:33.320
and understand their feelings.

44
00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:35.280
The word choice between the two situations

45
00:02:35.280 --> 00:02:38.360
is very similar, but the action.

46
00:02:38.360 --> 00:02:41.900
The action you take by looking at it from their perspective

47
00:02:41.900 --> 00:02:44.340
is what empathy is all about.

48
00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:46.360
Some days it's hard to empathize.

49
00:02:46.360 --> 00:02:48.140
I know from experience.

50
00:02:48.140 --> 00:02:50.840
Maybe you've had an argument with a loved one before work.

51
00:02:50.840 --> 00:02:52.020
Then by the end of the day,

52
00:02:52.020 --> 00:02:55.600
you find yourself getting annoyed or upset with users.

53
00:02:55.600 --> 00:02:57.520
That's the moment when empathy becomes the more

54
00:02:57.540 --> 00:03:04.100
most important because anyone can showcase empathy when it's easy, but someone who persistently

55
00:03:04.100 --> 00:03:11.380
displays empathy will stand out as a kinder human and a more professional and effective employee.

56
00:03:11.380 --> 00:03:17.140
Once you have empathy down, you should think of your tone. Tone is historically thought of as

57
00:03:17.140 --> 00:03:22.980
how you speak out loud. In this technological age, when many of our interactions are over text,

58
00:03:22.980 --> 00:03:27.380
and IT support is increasingly done remotely, tone isn't just about how you speak out loud.

59
00:03:27.380 --> 00:03:30.500
how you come off during an in-person conversation.

60
00:03:30.500 --> 00:03:34.740
It's expanded into how you write, punctuate, and even spell.

61
00:03:34.740 --> 00:03:37.420
If your tone is short or blunt,

62
00:03:37.420 --> 00:03:40.300
then the user will feel brushed off and devalued.

63
00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:42.780
But if your tone is friendly and curious,

64
00:03:42.780 --> 00:03:45.560
the user is much more likely to have a positive experience

65
00:03:45.560 --> 00:03:46.880
working with you.

66
00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:49.580
Be careful not to go overboard with the friendliness, though.

67
00:03:49.580 --> 00:03:51.580
It could be disingenuous.

68
00:03:51.580 --> 00:03:54.980
Communicating a good tone is a delicate balance.

69
00:03:54.980 --> 00:03:57.360
How you ask a question and how you respond to

70
00:03:57.380 --> 00:03:59.380
a user's question matters.

71
00:03:59.380 --> 00:04:01.820
Let's say you tell a user in an email,

72
00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:03.820
turn your computer off and on again,

73
00:04:03.820 --> 00:04:05.460
and it will start working.

74
00:04:05.460 --> 00:04:07.220
They'll probably never respond,

75
00:04:07.220 --> 00:04:09.720
and your company may have lost a customer

76
00:04:09.720 --> 00:04:13.540
because the tone is just too short and pretty unfriendly.

77
00:04:13.540 --> 00:04:14.800
Well, it gets to the point,

78
00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:18.260
it doesn't leave the door open to a conversation.

79
00:04:18.260 --> 00:04:19.899
What if instead you wrote,

80
00:04:19.899 --> 00:04:23.000
please try turning your computer off and back on again?

81
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:25.840
This should update the change we made and fix the problem.

82
00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:27.280
If that doesn't work, just let me.

83
00:04:27.380 --> 00:04:32.880
me know. It's a little wordier, but it has a better tone of asking versus telling, inviting

84
00:04:32.880 --> 00:04:38.060
them back to connect with you in case the issue isn't resolved leaves the lines of communication

85
00:04:38.060 --> 00:04:42.320
open. Tone can be especially difficult when you're supporting someone in a different region

86
00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:47.900
or country. Make sure to familiarize yourself with a local style, whether that's more conversational

87
00:04:47.900 --> 00:04:54.040
or direct, and adjust yourself depending on the audience. In this day and age of text and email,

88
00:04:54.040 --> 00:04:57.360
it's easy to ignore what someone says. If a comment seems to be a comment seems to be able to be.

89
00:04:57.380 --> 00:05:00.380
like a dig or it's just too much information provided,

90
00:05:00.380 --> 00:05:02.380
we tend to shy away from responding.

91
00:05:02.380 --> 00:05:05.380
It's also really common to forget to tell the user

92
00:05:05.380 --> 00:05:07.380
what you're doing while you're troubleshooting.

93
00:05:07.380 --> 00:05:10.380
That might leave the user waiting in an awkward silence.

94
00:05:10.380 --> 00:05:13.380
Whenever possible, acknowledge the user.

95
00:05:13.380 --> 00:05:15.380
This reduces the tension that might build

96
00:05:15.380 --> 00:05:19.380
and helps you understand how you're working toward a solution.

97
00:05:19.380 --> 00:05:21.380
Let's say you're chatting back and forth with the user.

98
00:05:21.380 --> 00:05:24.380
You're asking a lot of questions to better troubleshoot the issue.

99
00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:26.380
The user is answering them, but also,

100
00:05:26.380 --> 00:05:32.140
them but also makes comments like, geez, I already answered these in my last email, or I

101
00:05:32.140 --> 00:05:34.440
just want to know what's causing my problem.

102
00:05:34.440 --> 00:05:38.120
You choose to ignore this and continue on with your troubleshooting.

103
00:05:38.120 --> 00:05:43.140
You think you're close to solving the problem, and these side comments are just a distraction.

104
00:05:43.140 --> 00:05:48.000
But then the user stops fully engaging with you and only gives you half answers to your questions.

105
00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.060
Now you're not able to solve the issue at all.

106
00:05:50.060 --> 00:05:53.760
The user's unhappy, you're unhappy, and the company's unhappy.

107
00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:55.260
It's a bad situation.

108
00:05:55.260 --> 00:05:57.900
Instead of ignoring the user in that situation,

109
00:05:57.900 --> 00:06:01.060
you could have said, I'm sorry for asking these questions.

110
00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:04.140
Sometimes repeating them will help new information pop up.

111
00:06:04.140 --> 00:06:08.140
Or you could have said, sorry for the repeat questions.

112
00:06:08.140 --> 00:06:10.440
I don't want to give you a superficial cause

113
00:06:10.440 --> 00:06:12.100
when we could fix the root issue,

114
00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:14.040
and you won't have to chat with us again.

115
00:06:14.040 --> 00:06:16.620
This helps them to understand your method

116
00:06:16.620 --> 00:06:18.640
and become part of the solution.

117
00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:20.940
It's important to acknowledge your own actions

118
00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:23.220
if you think they might otherwise confuse the user.

119
00:06:23.220 --> 00:06:25.240
Let's say a user contacts you to fix something.

120
00:06:25.260 --> 00:06:28.260
After collecting some information, you go radio silent.

121
00:06:28.260 --> 00:06:40.885
What the user to do Would they ask if you still there Would they wait awkwardly until you came back on the line How long would they wait before ending the call or saying something How would they feel about their interaction with you

122
00:06:41.285 --> 00:06:41.985
Pretty awkward.

123
00:06:42.505 --> 00:06:45.665
But what if you said, I need to do some research on this issue.

124
00:06:46.125 --> 00:06:48.805
Would you mind waiting about five minutes or less while I do that?

125
00:06:49.245 --> 00:06:52.345
They'd probably say short and keep themselves occupied while they wait.

126
00:06:52.905 --> 00:06:55.905
They'd also feel more confident in your ability to resolve the issue.

127
00:06:55.905 --> 00:06:59.425
This leads to the most important thing to remember when working with people,

128
00:06:59.425 --> 00:07:01.745
And that's developing trust.

129
00:07:02.285 --> 00:07:04.665
This is easy to do if you have repeat users.

130
00:07:05.025 --> 00:07:06.445
They see you every workday.

131
00:07:06.965 --> 00:07:11.185
One bad day isn't going to stop them from trusting that you know what you're doing.

132
00:07:11.625 --> 00:07:16.745
But in a transactional user base where the user only contacts the company once or twice,

133
00:07:17.185 --> 00:07:22.405
how you interact with each user each time is going to break or build that trust.

134
00:07:23.044 --> 00:07:24.505
Why is trust so important?

135
00:07:25.025 --> 00:07:27.345
Without it, the user could be difficult to work with

136
00:07:27.345 --> 00:07:29.845
and could even ignore your advice completely.

137
00:07:29.845 --> 00:07:33.645
Empathy and acknowledgement are a big part of building trust.

138
00:07:33.645 --> 00:07:36.645
Without these, you'll find it difficult to connect with the user.

139
00:07:36.645 --> 00:07:39.345
By seeing things from the user's perspective,

140
00:07:39.345 --> 00:07:43.345
you're more likely to find a solution that will help them specifically.

141
00:07:43.345 --> 00:07:45.845
This lets them know that you care,

142
00:07:45.845 --> 00:07:48.845
and they'll be more likely to be engaged in the interaction.

143
00:07:48.845 --> 00:07:52.845
It's also important to follow through on your commitments and promises.

144
00:07:52.845 --> 00:07:55.345
If you tell someone you're going to follow up in one hour,

145
00:07:55.345 --> 00:07:56.845
then be sure to make it happen.

146
00:07:56.845 --> 00:08:00.385
And if you don't, acknowledge the oversight and apologize.

147
00:08:01.125 --> 00:08:03.665
Be sure that any claims you make can be backed up.

148
00:08:04.145 --> 00:08:07.225
Don't make something up to a user because you think it'll help in the moment.

149
00:08:07.845 --> 00:08:11.465
Be honest with the user, even if you think they won't be happy about it.

150
00:08:11.725 --> 00:08:13.725
And never be afraid to admit when you're wrong.

151
00:08:14.245 --> 00:08:16.425
This might be the hardest thing to do with the user,

152
00:08:16.825 --> 00:08:19.745
but you'll find that your interactions are more successful this way.

153
00:08:20.145 --> 00:08:24.025
Being specific and empathetic with your apologies will give it more meaning.

154
00:08:24.785 --> 00:08:26.825
And remember, no one wakes up.

155
00:08:26.845 --> 00:08:30.445
in the morning thinking, I'm going to be a jerk today.

156
00:08:30.445 --> 00:08:34.525
While you shouldn't sacrifice your self-respect, do your best to give the user the benefit

157
00:08:34.525 --> 00:08:36.684
of the doubt whenever possible.

158
00:08:40.684 --> 00:08:44.445
Now that we've covered the main customer service techniques, we're going to dive into some

159
00:08:44.445 --> 00:08:50.845
of the nitty-gritty by looking at the anatomy of an interaction. These apply to any channel of IT

160
00:08:50.845 --> 00:08:56.685
support, email, phone, chat, or in-person interactions. From the first,

161
00:08:56.845 --> 00:09:02.345
moment you interact with someone, it's important to think about how you say hello.

162
00:09:02.345 --> 00:09:04.505
Do you make sure to tell them your name?

163
00:09:04.505 --> 00:09:07.845
Do you incorporate information you know about them in your greeting?

164
00:09:07.845 --> 00:09:09.725
Do you ensure a positive tone?

165
00:09:09.725 --> 00:09:12.025
Are your spelling and grammar on point?

166
00:09:12.025 --> 00:09:15.964
These are all ways to create a really good start to the interaction.

167
00:09:15.964 --> 00:09:18.084
Some of these things are hard to achieve though.

168
00:09:18.084 --> 00:09:21.845
I'm a horrible speller, especially when I'm in a hurry.

169
00:09:21.845 --> 00:09:25.885
But knowing some of these trouble spots ahead of time will let you find ways to address

170
00:09:25.885 --> 00:09:32.125
them before the interaction. For me, I know that when I'm in a hurry, I need to recheck my spelling

171
00:09:32.125 --> 00:09:38.425
before hitting send. Have you ever heard the phrase, first impressions last a lifetime? Well, that might

172
00:09:38.425 --> 00:09:44.285
be a bit of an exaggeration. It touches on some truth. How you first interact with someone will

173
00:09:44.285 --> 00:09:50.305
influence how the rest of the interaction plays out. I'm not saying you have to be over-the-top,

174
00:09:50.305 --> 00:09:55.765
gushy and nice. That might have the opposite effect. Just be professional. Acknowledge the user.

175
00:09:55.885 --> 00:09:57.885
and show them some respect.

176
00:09:57.885 --> 00:10:00.885
Taking the time to get the interaction off to a good start

177
00:10:00.885 --> 00:10:03.885
will make everything that comes after easier.

